tools_called.args:
{"summary": "For reducing chemical use in agriculture, multiple studies show positive effects on bats. Four studies evaluated reducing pesticide, herbicide and fertiliser use on bat populations across Mexico, Portugal, Germany and Columbia. These found that farms with few or no chemical inputs had higher overall bat activity and abundance than those using high chemical inputs, different bat species compositions, higher diversity of insect-eating bats, and better body condition scores for bats in areas using no chemicals. One specific study in Portugal found farms with few or no chemicals had different bat species compositions and higher overall bat activity than high chemical input farms. Another study in Columbia found bats in silvopastoral areas using no chemicals had higher body weights and condition scores than those in conventional farming areas.

For changing effluent treatments to reduce pollution impacts on bats, no evidence was found. One action examined changing effluent treatments used in agriculture and forestry specifically noted "We found no studies that evaluated the effects of changing the effluent treatments used in agriculture and forestry on bat populations."

The evidence base shows clear benefits for reducing chemical use in agriculture for bat conservation, while there is currently no available evidence assessing the effectiveness of changing effluent treatment practices.", "query": "To reduce the impact of pollution on bats, what is the evidence for the effectiveness of changing effluent treatments versus reducing chemical use in agriculture?", "action_ids": ["2013", "2331", "1016"]}

