{"query": "What are the most effective types of artificial roosts for bats?", "summary": "Based on available evidence, bat boxes are the most studied and widely used type of artificial roost for bats. A review of 44 studies found that 72 bat species used bat boxes, with 18 species using them commonly and 31 species using them as maternity roosts. Studies show bats used bat boxes in various habitats including forests, farmland, wetlands, and urban areas. Bat box effectiveness varies by design, with black boxes preferred over lighter colors, and multi-chamber designs showing higher occupancy. Larger boxes tend to have higher occupancy rates. Position affects success, with boxes on buildings showing higher occupancy than those on trees in some studies.

Artificial caves or hibernacula are also effective, with four studies finding that these structures were used by up to four bat species, and one study reporting increasing bat numbers over nine years after construction.

Limited evidence exists for other types of artificial roosts. Creating alternative roosts within developments showed mixed results, with bats using purpose-built roosts at 13-74% of development sites, though bats used new roosts in lower numbers than original roosts in some cases. Artificial tree hollows had some success, with eight of 16 hollows being used by long-eared bats in one study.", "action_ids": ["1024", "2049", "949", "2047"]}

